      "cipher_title": "Encryption algorithm",
      "cipher_desc": "AEAD algorithm used to encrypt and authenticate the vault file",
      "cipher_gcm_note": "Fast, hardware-accelerated, widely supported. Recommended for most users.",
      "cipher_gcm_more": "AES-256-GCM is an AEAD (Authenticated Encryption with Associated Data) mode standardized by NIST (FIPS 197). It uses a 128-bit authentication tag (GHASH) and a 12-byte random nonce generated fresh at every save. Supported natively by AES-NI hardware acceleration on all modern processors. It is the de-facto standard in TLS 1.3, iOS, Android, and most cloud services. The probability of nonce collision is negligible for normal use (one vault file, saved thousands of times).",
      "cipher_gcm_siv_note": "Nonce-misuse resistant (RFC 8452). Ideal if your system's random generator is unreliable.",
      "cipher_gcm_siv_more": "AES-256-GCM-SIV (RFC 8452) is a variant of GCM that derives a synthetic IV (SIV) from the plaintext and the encryption key rather than relying on a unique random nonce. If the same nonce is accidentally reused — for example due to a faulty random generator — confidentiality is still preserved (only the ability to detect tampering is slightly weakened). Marginally slower than GCM due to an extra PRF pass, but offers stronger safety guarantees in contexts where entropy is limited.",
      "cipher_xchacha_note": "192-bit nonce, pure software cipher. No hardware dependency.",
      "cipher_xchacha_more": "XChaCha20-Poly1305 combines the XChaCha20 stream cipher (an extension of ChaCha20 by Daniel J. Bernstein with a 192-bit nonce) with the Poly1305 MAC for authentication. It requires no dedicated hardware (no AES-NI), runs at constant time on all platforms, and is immune to timing side-channels. A 192-bit nonce makes accidental nonce reuse effectively impossible even across billions of encryptions. Used by WireGuard, libsodium, and Signal. Excellent choice for security-critical environments or cross-platform deployments.",
      "cipher_tip": "The cipher change is applied when you click Save. If a vault is open, it will be re-encrypted immediately.",
